==Old English==

===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*haila-'', from Indo-European ''*kailo-'' ‘healthy, intact, well-omened’. Cognate with Old Frisian [[hel|hēl]], Old Saxon [[hel|hēl]] (Dutch [[heel]], [[geheel]] ‘healthy’), Old High German [[heil]] (German [[heil]] ‘healthy’), Old Norse [[heill]] (Swedish [[hel]] ‘whole’), Gothic [[𐌷𐌰𐌹𐌻𐍃]]. The IE root is also the source of Greek [[κοιλυ|κοῖλυ]] ‘goodness, beauty’, Welsh [[coel]] ‘sign’, Old Church Slavonic [[целъ]] (Russian [[целый]] ‘whole, healthy’).

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/ha:l/}}

===Adjective===
(ġe)'''hāl'''
# [[sound]], [[healthy]], [[intact]]
#:''Iosep axode hwæðer hira fæder wære hal'': Joseph asked whether their father were well. (''Genesis'')
# [[whole]], undivided

===Descendents===
*English [[whole]], [[hale]]


